<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="38" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,1061,1204]" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,351,1061,1087]" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">Remarks:—</emphasis>
The short-stalked, bright red ascomata in combination with the presence of fumarprotocetraric acid set this species well apart from all Guianas lichens. The only similar species is 
<taxonomicName authority="Stenroos" authorityName="S. Stenroos" authorityYear="1989" box="[151,434,1139,1165]" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Cladoniaceae" genus="Cladonia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Lecanorales" pageId="13" pageNumber="38" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="ahtii">
<emphasis box="[151,321,1139,1164]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">Cladonia ahtii</emphasis>
Stenroos
</taxonomicName>
, known from SE 
<collectingCountry box="[641,715,1139,1165]" name="Brazil" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, which belongs to the group of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="G. Meyer" authorityYear="1825" box="[1089,1213,1139,1164]" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Cladoniaceae" genus="Cladonia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Lecanorales" pageId="13" pageNumber="38" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="miniata">
<emphasis box="[1089,1213,1139,1164]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="38">C. miniata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and differs by the shape of the squamules, thick and rounded, with a flat to concave upper surface.
</paragraph>
